View Tiddlers

View tiddlers are wikitext tiddlers that render inside layout slots. They should be tagged with `$:/tags/rimir/appify/view` so the edit-mode view selector can discover them. Views are assigned via `appify-view-<slot>` fields on the app tiddler or via the `views` array in the splits config JSON.

Binding a view to a slot:

```
set_field(title="<appTitle>", field="appify-view-sidebar", value="MyApp/sidebar-view")
```

Reading a view's source:

Use `get_tiddler(title)` to read the full wikitext. This is what you modify with `set_field(field="text")`.

Common wikitext patterns in views:

Navigation list (clickable items that set a channel):
```
<$list filter="Alpha Bravo Charlie">
<$button>
<$action-statewrap-set channel="project" value=<<currentTiddler>>/>
<<currentTiddler>>
</$button>
</$list>
```

Conditional rendering (show content based on channel):
```
<%if [statewrap-get[project]!is[blank]]%>
  Project is selected: <$text text={{{[statewrap-get[project]]}}}/>
<%else%>
  Select a project
<%endif%>
```

Tab buttons (mutually exclusive selection):
```
<$button class={{{ [statewrap-get[tab]match[overview]then[active]else[]] }}}>
<$action-statewrap-set channel="tab" value="overview"/>
Overview
</$button>
```

Reveal panel (show/hide based on channel value):
```
<$reveal stateTitle={{{[statewrap-ref[tab]]}}} type="match" text="overview">
  Content for overview tab
</$reveal>
```

Dynamic macro-based data:
```
\procedure items-Alpha() Design Build Test
\procedure items-Bravo() Research Plan Execute

<$set name="proj" value={{{[statewrap-get[project]]}}}>
<$list filter="[<proj>addprefix[items-]getvariable[]enlist-input[]]" variable="item">
  <<item>>
</$list>
</$set>
```
This pattern stores data in macros keyed by channel value.

Modifying a view:

1. Read current wikitext with get_tiddler
2. Understand the structure (macros, lists, reveals, channels used)
3. Write updated wikitext with set_field(field="text", value="new wikitext")

Important: Preserve the existing patterns. If a view uses `\procedure` macros for data, add new entries in the same pattern. If it uses `$list filter="..."`, add items to that filter.

Creating a new view:

1. Create a tiddler with `type: text/vnd.tiddlywiki` and tag `$:/tags/rimir/appify/view`
2. Write wikitext using statewrap channels for reactivity
3. Assign it to a slot via the edit-mode view selector dropdown, or by writing the splits config JSON

Cloning a view:

Use `<$action-appify-clone-view>` to clone an existing view into the user's namespace:
```
<$action-appify-clone-view app="AppTitle" slot="main.0" tiddler="SourceView"/>
```
This creates a copy at `<clone-prefix>/views/<baseName>`, adds the view tag, and updates the split config reference. Available as a button in edit mode.

Gotchas:

`\function` bodies cannot use `statewrap-get` or other tree-dependent filter operators. TW evaluates `\function` bodies via `makeFakeWidgetWithVariables()` — a disconnected object without `parentWidget`. Operators that walk up the widget tree (like `statewrap-get` looking for a `<$statewrap>` ancestor) will silently return empty.

Use `\procedure` + `[subfilter<>]` instead:
```
\procedure my-entity-type() [statewrap-get[section]match[projects]then[project]] ~[statewrap-get[section]match[people]then[person]]

<$let entityType={{{ [subfilter<my-entity-type>] }}}>
```

Do NOT use:
```
\function my.entity-type() [statewrap-get[section]match[projects]then[project]] ~...

<$let entityType={{{ [function[my.entity-type]] }}}>
```

The `[subfilter<>]` operator evaluates the filter with the real widget context, preserving the full parent chain so `statewrap-get` can find the statewrap wrapper.

Widget attributes cannot concatenate variable refs with literals. `$tiddler=<<var>>:suffix` does NOT work — TW only sees the `<<var>>` part.

Use a filter attribute instead:
```
<$action-setfield $tiddler={{{ [<myState>addsuffix[:last-click]] }}} text=""/>
```

Or pre-compute with `<$let>`:
```
<$let fullTitle={{{ [<myState>addsuffix[:last-click]] }}}>
<$action-setfield $tiddler=<<fullTitle>> text=""/>
</$let>
```

`statewrap-get` returns the OLD value during the same action sequence. After `<$action-statewrap-set channel="x" value="new"/>`, calling `statewrap-get[x]` in a subsequent action still returns the pre-set value. The widget variable context only updates on the next refresh cycle.

Do NOT read back a channel you just wrote:
```
<$action-statewrap-set channel="expanded" value=<<item>>/>
<!-- WRONG: statewrap-get still returns the old value here -->
<$action-setfield $tiddler=<<state>> text={{{ [statewrap-get[expanded]match<item>then[yes]] }}}/>
```

Instead, compute the dependent value from source data directly:
```
<$action-statewrap-set channel="expanded" value=<<item>>/>
<$action-setfield $tiddler=<<state>> text={{{ [all[tiddlers]rrt.type[note]field:parent<item>first[]] }}}/>
```

`$macrocall` renders procedure output in inline mode. Block-level HTML (`<div>`, `<table>`, `<h*>`) inside a `\procedure` gets swallowed when called via `$macrocall`.

Use `<$transclude $variable="proc-name" $mode="block"/>` instead:
```
<!-- WRONG — block content invisible -->
<$macrocall $name="my-view" entity=<<item>>/>

<!-- RIGHT — block content renders correctly -->
<$transclude $variable="my-view" entity=<<item>> $mode="block"/>
```

Action widgets inside `<%else%>` branches are NOT reachable by `Widget.invokeActions()`. The `<%if%>` compiles to a ListWidget that stores the else branch in `elseChildren`, which `invokeActions` does not traverse.

Use `<$list>` with `emptyMessage` for action widgets instead:
```
<!-- WRONG — actions in <%else%> never fire -->
<%if [<result>!is[blank]] %>
  <$action-setfield .../>
<%else%>
  <$action-setfield .../> <!-- unreachable! -->
<%endif%>

<!-- RIGHT — emptyMessage actions are reachable -->
<$list filter="[<result>!is[blank]]" variable="_">
  <$action-setfield .../>
</$list>
```
Note: Read-only rendering (capturing `textContent`) works fine with `<%if%>` — the bug only affects action invocation.

See also: llm_help("appify/channels") — how channels work, llm_help("appify/splits") — splitting a slot into sub-panes
